==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|thider}}, from {{inh|en|ang|þider}}, an alteration (probably by analogy with {{m|ang|hider||hither}}) of earlier {{m|ang|þæder|t=to there}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*þadrê}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈðɪðəɹ/|/ˈθɪðəɹ/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-thither.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɪðə(r)}}

===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}

# {{lb|en|chiefly|literary|_|or|_|legal|dated}} To that place.
#* {{RQ:KJV|Genesis|19|20}}
#*: Behold now, this city is near to flee unto, and it is a little one: Oh, let me escape '''thither'''
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1661|author={{w|Robert Boyle}}|title=[[s:Sceptical Chymist|The Sceptical Chymist]]|page=9|passage={{...}} Eleutherius, who thinking himself concern'd, because he brought me '''thither''' {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1886|translator=H.L. Br&aelig;kstad|author=Peter Christen Asbj&oslash;rnsen|authorlink=Peter Christen Asbj&oslash;rnsen|title=Folk and Fairy Tales|page=280|passage=But the road left the river again; there were certainly twistings and turnings, as the old woman had said, for at one moment it wound hither and the next '''thither''', and at some places it was almost imperceptible.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1922|author={{w|James Joyce}}|title=[[w:Ulysses (novel)|Ulysses]]|section=Episode 12, ''The Cyclops''|passage=And there rises a shining palace whose crystal glittering roof is seen by mariners who traverse the extensive sea in barks built expressly for that purpose, and '''thither''' come all herds and fatlings and firstfruits of that land for O'Connell Fitzsimon takes toll of them, a chieftain descended from chieftains.}}
# {{lb|en|dated}} To that point, end, or result.
#: {{ux|en|The argument tended '''thither'''.}}

